00:00:35.645 --> 00:00:38.210
- Welcome to A Conversation
With History, I'm Harry Kreisler

00:00:38.210 --> 00:00:40.910
of the Institute of International Studies.

00:00:40.910 --> 00:00:44.050
Our guest today is Stephen S. Cohen

00:00:44.050 --> 00:00:47.213
who is professor in the Graduate School,

00:00:48.830 --> 00:00:51.130
the University of California at Berkeley

00:00:51.130 --> 00:00:55.610
and he's also co-director
of the Berkeley Roundtable

00:00:55.610 --> 00:00:58.160
on the International
Economy also at Berkeley.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:02.020
He's a senior fellow at
the New America Foundation

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:07.020
in Washington and he's just
written with Brad DeLong,

00:01:07.090 --> 00:01:11.080
The End of Influence, What
Happens When Other Countries

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:12.403
Have The Money.

00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:15.647
Steve, welcome to our program.

00:01:15.647 --> 00:01:17.410
- Good to be here with you, Harry.

00:01:17.410 --> 00:01:19.080
- Where were you born and raised?

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:20.310
- New York.

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:22.840
- And looking back, how
do you think your parents

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:24.690
shaped your thinking about the world?

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:27.150
- Oh my god, that's a hard question,

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:29.673
you told me you guys didn't
play with easy questions.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:39.373
They kind of applauded if you
were reasonable and realistic,

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:44.750
and didn't think,

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:47.580
or weren't all that
impressed if you could cite

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:49.903
the great religious authorities.

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:55.030
- And was there a lot of
discussion about politics

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:57.220
and the economy around the dinner table

00:01:57.220 --> 00:01:58.410
or did that come later?

00:01:58.410 --> 00:01:59.780
- That came later.

00:01:59.780 --> 00:02:02.410
- And what got you interested

00:02:03.373 --> 00:02:08.373
in pursuing degrees in the
field of politics and economics?

00:02:10.323 --> 00:02:12.710
- I was an undergraduate.

00:02:12.710 --> 00:02:14.000
- [Harry] Where did you do your undergrad?

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:15.190
- Williams College.

00:02:15.190 --> 00:02:16.023
- [Harry] Aha.

00:02:16.023 --> 00:02:18.820
- For young boys of
good family at the time.

00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:21.990
They've subsequently never (mumbles)

00:02:22.930 --> 00:02:27.550
And I was a major in political
science and economics

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:29.400
and I couldn't tell 'em,

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.330
I didn't know where one
ended and the other began.

00:02:32.330 --> 00:02:34.400
I've had a lifelong difficulty.

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:37.170
Is this economics? Is this politics?

00:02:37.170 --> 00:02:38.553
So I kind of did both.

00:02:40.370 --> 00:02:45.275
- And then from there, you
went on to graduate school and?

00:02:45.275 --> 00:02:47.175
- Oh, there was a little interruption.

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:52.240
I was too early as an undergraduate editor

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:54.410
of the college magazine.

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:58.543
The Dean called me into
his office, and said,

00:02:59.444 --> 00:03:00.847
"I'm giving you a choice.

00:03:00.847 --> 00:03:03.763
"A, you're out of here
today, I'm throwing you out.

00:03:04.804 --> 00:03:06.880
"Or B, you stop editing that thing

00:03:08.237 --> 00:03:10.630
"and go take a junior year abroad."

00:03:10.630 --> 00:03:12.557
And I said Paris, he said, "Done."

00:03:13.510 --> 00:03:16.040
- And what was he objecting
to, a particular article?

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:17.070
- [Stephen] Oh, yes.

00:03:17.070 --> 00:03:20.800
- Or a general tone of...

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:22.710
- First it was the tone and then there was

00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:24.113
a particular piece.

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.933
Looking back it was kind of obnoxious.

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:33.000
It was about some poor guy there

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.410
who taught a course on
religion and sex and love

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:38.090
in the Bible among other things,

00:03:38.090 --> 00:03:42.010
and was up to be president
of a small college nearby.

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:43.460
So I wrote a little limerick.

00:03:44.463 --> 00:03:46.760
- I see, so it was off to Paris.

00:03:46.760 --> 00:03:50.219
- Jointly signed with the daughter

00:03:50.219 --> 00:03:53.250
of the chairman of the board
of trustees of that College

00:03:53.250 --> 00:03:55.993
who's an undergraduate
at Smith at the time.

00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:58.730
For that, you should be tossed.

00:03:58.730 --> 00:04:00.030
I mean it was just awful.

00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:03.900
- I see, so do you get more discipline

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:09.670
in Paris or was it rather you were exposed

00:04:09.670 --> 00:04:11.840
to the culture and stayed with it--

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:13.337
- I don't think it was
more about discipline

00:04:13.337 --> 00:04:16.370
and so much as exposure to the world.

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:20.330
And of all places to
think about an economy,

00:04:20.330 --> 00:04:24.820
France, never accepted
the kind of economics

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:26.740
we mainstream here.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:29.043
The difference in the
government and the...

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:31.961
didn't make sense to anybody,

00:04:31.961 --> 00:04:33.080
that the government was the referee.

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:35.050
No, the government is
the partner of everything

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:35.973
and every one.

00:04:37.076 --> 00:04:38.965
The state not the government.

00:04:38.965 --> 00:04:41.370
- Did that experience give you a focus

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:43.610
so that you now really
kind of have a sense

00:04:43.610 --> 00:04:45.743
of what you wanted to do--

00:04:45.743 --> 00:04:46.610
- Well, it didn't give me any focus,

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:48.470
I really had a great time.

00:04:48.470 --> 00:04:52.080
So much to see and do and learn,
how to learn about eating,

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:54.680
how to learn about art,
it was just endless.

00:04:54.680 --> 00:04:57.843
And when I got back, this
one professor called me,

00:04:57.843 --> 00:04:59.677
"And what was your project?"

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:03.520
I thought, (blabbers).

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:08.080
I started looking at
French economic planning.

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:09.180
- [Harry] I see.

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:12.603
- So he said very good, write
a paper about it so I did.

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:18.253
And then I went off to graduate school.

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:21.853
First I applied to law school a few times.

00:05:25.361 --> 00:05:27.730
And the Harvard Law
School has that catalog,

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:31.550
the Facebook, the pictures
of the incoming class.

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:34.430
If you look under Cohen,
not only comes Steve Cohen

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:37.880
'cause a few of it, there's
one photo missing, that was me.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:40.160
- I see, so you got
accepted but didn't go.

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:43.650
- I actually wrote a stupid letter,

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:44.850
still wise guy kid.

00:05:44.850 --> 00:05:47.040
I looked upon entering
the Harvard Law School

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:49.900
as a symbol of my own
total defeat in life.

00:05:49.900 --> 00:05:51.557
- I see, I see.

00:05:51.557 --> 00:05:53.700
And they didn't take
kindly to that, I guess.

00:05:53.700 --> 00:05:55.480
- Oh, they care a lot.

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:58.703
I'm sure they were not in
the least bit disturbed.

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:04.080
'Cause I applied the year after
and they admitted me again,

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:07.028
I didn't go again. (laughs)

00:06:07.028 --> 00:06:09.340
And then I went to the London School.

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:11.033
- And focusing on?

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.540
Politics and the--

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:15.373
- I did it.

00:06:16.646 --> 00:06:18.720
And they had a, you
might call it a program

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:20.740
where you could do both.

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:23.670
So I did and I ended up doing a thesis on?

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:24.510
- French planning.

00:06:24.510 --> 00:06:26.460
- French economic planning, you see?

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:28.233
The littlest, they stick you.

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:33.850
- What was it, just to
be clear about this,

00:06:33.850 --> 00:06:37.130
what was it that led to this focus?

00:06:37.130 --> 00:06:39.750
You think that experience,
junior year abroad

00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:42.730
and then you found this whole interface

00:06:42.730 --> 00:06:45.400
between the two realms very significant?

00:06:45.400 --> 00:06:46.950
- It sounds so noble.

00:06:46.950 --> 00:06:50.380
It was that experience and
the need, that afternoon,

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:52.850
to have a subject for that professor

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:55.210
in half an hour.

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:56.863
There I had a, so I kept going.

00:06:57.710 --> 00:07:02.710
And that was, in those
days a thesis at LSE was,

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:05.140
the idea was you'd write a book.

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:09.070
Not an article or two articles

00:07:09.070 --> 00:07:11.410
that shows you can play,

00:07:11.410 --> 00:07:15.230
they do all the necessary
tricks, he wrote a book.

00:07:15.230 --> 00:07:19.840
So I wrote this book and it
came out at Harvard Press,

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:24.300
called Modern Capitalist
Planning, something like that.

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:26.530
- I actually have it,
Modern Capitalist Planning,

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:29.793
The French Model, right.

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:36.450
What did you learn in
the writing of that book

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:38.750
and the research it entail?

00:07:38.750 --> 00:07:42.840
I mean did it raise you to a new level

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:44.393
in seeing this interface?

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:48.070
- First it was all about the interface.

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:51.023
The state, business, the economy.

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:54.253
And where it's all seen as one.

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:57.960
And I started looking around the world

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:02.960
and the country's making
important changes, rapid growth,

00:08:03.190 --> 00:08:05.823
changes where they go, Japan.

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:10.550
And you see the enormous role of policy

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:14.370
of the actions of the state in steering it

00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:15.403
and enabling it.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:19.510
And that in a funny way set me up

00:08:19.510 --> 00:08:21.273
for an understanding of Japan.

00:08:22.450 --> 00:08:24.860
When, they used to be those big arguments.

00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:27.760
There was no argument
Japan was doing well.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:29.850
- This would be now in the 80s--

00:08:29.850 --> 00:08:34.000
- No, the 70s and the 80s, 70s and 80s.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:35.800
Japan was definitely doing well,

00:08:35.800 --> 00:08:38.620
there was no question, fabulously.

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:43.030
And there was a whole, I think a majority

00:08:43.030 --> 00:08:45.690
of American economists saying,

00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:48.060
well, the state is too involved,

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:50.690
they should get out of everything.

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:54.363
And no one in Japan thought
this made any sense whatsoever.

00:08:55.715 --> 00:08:57.620
Makes no sense.

00:08:57.620 --> 00:09:01.920
And it was easier for me to understand

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:05.200
what the Japanese thought they were doing

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:07.540
'cause I thought of it in French,

00:09:07.540 --> 00:09:10.340
as opposed to thinking
of it in Anglo-Saxon

00:09:10.340 --> 00:09:11.740
as the French would call it.

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:19.290
That kind of carried through
in most things I have done.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:22.590
- Now this raises an interesting question

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:26.610
because what we've learned
here is that you wound up

00:09:26.610 --> 00:09:29.830
going abroad to see this connection,

00:09:29.830 --> 00:09:34.830
and that turned you in essence
into a political economist,

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:38.970
I guess one would say,
which is not something

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:43.684
that grows naturally in
the American environment.

00:09:43.684 --> 00:09:46.234
- And now you find us under
glass in a few museums.

00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:48.609
We don't do that.

00:09:48.609 --> 00:09:51.080
- Well, you're brought
out from under the glass

00:09:51.978 --> 00:09:54.380
when there's a crisis in
the system which leads us

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:55.584
kind of a--

00:09:55.584 --> 00:09:57.790
- And we have crises
rather frequently nowadays.

00:09:57.790 --> 00:10:01.520
- Now, so let's say that the students

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:05.900
want to figure out how to
develop the skills to do this.

00:10:05.900 --> 00:10:07.610
How do you prepare?

00:10:07.610 --> 00:10:12.610
What is it you have to learn
in the way of a skill set

00:10:12.870 --> 00:10:16.223
to do political economics well?

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:23.969
- You have to first
learn to be marginalized.

00:10:23.969 --> 00:10:26.970
- (laughs) So live with being an outsider?

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:29.693
- Normal career paths closed.

00:10:31.065 --> 00:10:35.953
No kidding around, it's a
closed shop in economics really.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:37.743
You don't do it.

00:10:37.743 --> 00:10:40.923
If you can't make an econometric
model, you can't utter it.

00:10:42.950 --> 00:10:45.410
And you can make very
powerful econometrics models

00:10:45.410 --> 00:10:48.063
at the expense of what you talk about.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:53.310
Has to be small and it's
built on a set of assumptions.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:58.110
- So, and this is something
I wanted to talk about it,

00:10:58.110 --> 00:11:02.460
is in comparing what you
do to what an economist

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:04.300
and the economics profession,

00:11:04.300 --> 00:11:08.773
you're saying there's a kind
of narrowness of the focus,

00:11:13.378 --> 00:11:15.210
an awe at the elegance of the theory

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:17.650
which may or may not relate
to what's actually going on

00:11:17.650 --> 00:11:18.660
in the real world.

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:19.510
- Oh, definitely.

00:11:20.680 --> 00:11:24.230
In fact I don't believe
as a requirement for a PhD

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:27.970
in most of the top economics departments.

00:11:27.970 --> 00:11:30.793
You were asked to know
anything about economic,

00:11:31.704 --> 00:11:34.743
the history of economic thought,
or about economic history.

00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:39.050
What had had happened out there and...

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:41.650
I think that's an egregious loss.

00:11:41.650 --> 00:11:43.340
- And also politics, right?

00:11:43.340 --> 00:11:45.230
I mean it isn't there--

00:11:45.230 --> 00:11:46.063
- [Stephen] They don't do politics.

00:11:46.063 --> 00:11:46.896
- Yeah, yeah.

00:11:46.896 --> 00:11:47.820
- The assumption...

00:11:50.475 --> 00:11:54.940
- So, in a way, a flaw here is that,

00:11:57.310 --> 00:12:01.340
there is a disconnect which
leads to a lack of understanding

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:04.680
of kind of the institutional setting,

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:06.970
the politics of the setting

00:12:06.970 --> 00:12:09.823
in which a particular
paradigm is embraced?

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:13.760
- Yeah, or viewed in another way.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:16.010
As an economist, there's a trade off.

00:12:16.010 --> 00:12:21.010
For the power of your analysis,
you sacrifice its relevance

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:22.183
and its range.

00:12:23.830 --> 00:12:27.060
And sometimes that comes
around to bite you badly.

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:31.621
- And I think we've already
learned from you that,

00:12:31.621 --> 00:12:34.800
in your particular case,
your analysis of France

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:39.800
contributed to the power
of your analysis of Japan

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:43.150
when that became an important issue,

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:45.730
that is the rise of the Japanese economy.

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:49.630
So what I'm hearing you
say is comparative studies

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:55.220
become very important that
is comparing case studies.

00:12:55.220 --> 00:12:56.940
- It absolutely helps to know something

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.130
about what's going on over there,

00:12:59.130 --> 00:13:00.630
especially when they interact.

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:04.970
- Now, you were a
co-founder and a co-director

00:13:04.970 --> 00:13:08.713
of the Berkeley Roundtable on
the International economy--

00:13:08.713 --> 00:13:10.190
- [Stephen] BRIE, like the cheese.

00:13:10.190 --> 00:13:12.040
- BRIE, like the cheese, of course,

00:13:12.040 --> 00:13:14.773
it would have to be because
of that junior year.

00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:16.553
That was what--

00:13:16.553 --> 00:13:18.680
- [Stephen] And most of those
years as a grad student also.

00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:23.650
- Right, so what then,
and talk a little about

00:13:24.577 --> 00:13:28.250
that group here at Berkeley,

00:13:28.250 --> 00:13:32.390
because it became important for the campus

00:13:32.390 --> 00:13:37.240
and internationally and sort
of understanding the trends

00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:41.410
and the world where political
economy was really important

00:13:41.410 --> 00:13:44.130
as we became less competitive

00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:46.740
and the rest of the world
became or some parts of it

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:48.680
became more competitive.

00:13:48.680 --> 00:13:50.560
- That's another one of these things.

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:53.460
Life's about a certain
nigh of the accidental.

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:57.393
I had spent two years
in New York previously,

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:01.713
sabbatical and some other I
don't remember what, fellowship.

00:14:05.750 --> 00:14:06.960
Most of it I spent hanging around

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:08.903
the Institute for Humanities at NYU.

00:14:10.522 --> 00:14:11.820
Where they gave me this marvelous office

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:13.900
and there were some interesting people.

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:16.490
- Great, did you read a
lot of novels or what...

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:19.493
- The novels were the nice part of it.

00:14:20.770 --> 00:14:23.560
Just studies of the
studies that criticized

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:27.223
the studies of the novels were
a little, not my favorite.

00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:31.040
But I came back.

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:32.840
When I got back, what am I gonna do?

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:36.443
And it's seeing, what do we have here?

00:14:38.060 --> 00:14:39.263
The great outdoors.

00:14:40.300 --> 00:14:41.280
- [Harry] California and me.

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:43.453
- Yeah, I'm not too good at that.

00:14:44.920 --> 00:14:47.750
Then there was strange and
exotic sexual practices

00:14:47.750 --> 00:14:48.583
at the time.

00:14:52.130 --> 00:14:55.269
I lucked out with an absolutely
lovely and beautiful wife.

00:14:55.269 --> 00:14:58.120
I wasn't gonna be good at it anyway.

00:14:58.120 --> 00:15:01.103
So that left technology,
which I knew nothing.

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:04.070
- It was fun to learn a little

00:15:04.070 --> 00:15:08.853
and semiconductors go into
everything, everything.

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:12.120
So all of a sudden, if
you follow the chip,

